ce allowed for over a century and respected by Congress until now. The issue is whether setting the federal Election Day applies the same rules as in 1845, which would invalidate modern voting methods and state laws. The dispute centers on the interpretation of Election Day statutes.\n  - id: 24-556, name: Fernandez v. United States, description: The case of Fernandez v. United States concerns whether district courts can consider errors or unfairness in a defendant\'s sentence when deciding if it is extraordinary and compelling to reduce the sentence, or if only personal circumstances like age and illness are relevant.\n  - id: 21-5726, name: Kemp v. United States, description: The case Kemp v. United States concerns the interpretation of Rule 60(b)(6) and whether it governs a particular legal issue, with the Petitioner arguing that Rule 60(b)(1) does not apply due to its focus on factual errors rather than legal ones.\n  - id: 21-1484, name: Arizona v. Navajo Nation, description: The case Arizona v. Navajo Nation is about whether the United States has a legal duty to provide water infrastructure for the Navajo Reservation, or if this responsibility lies with the tribe itself.\n  - id: 24-1234, name: United States v. Hemani, description: The case of United States v. Hemani, docket number 24-1234, concerns whether the government can temporarily disarm habitual marijuana users who continue to use the substance frequently. The issue revolves around a law that restricts Second Amendment rights for individuals who pose a perceived public safety risk due to their drug use.\n  - id: 22-58, name: United States v. Texas, description: The case centers on a dispute over the US government\'s immigration enforcement priorities, with the issue being whether states have standing to challenge federal policies and whether the government must apprehend and remove all non-citizens as required by law.\n  - id: 25-5, name: Noem, Sec. of Homeland v. Al Otro Lado, description: The case centers on the interpretation of a statute regarding when an alien \'arrives in the United States,\' with Petitioners arguing that the protections of a refugee convention and withholding-of-deportation statute do not extend to aliens outside U.S. soil.\n\nFollow these rules:\n- Extract parameters strictly according to the schema.\n- Apply the extraction instructions above.\n- Use context only when the user refers indirectly (e.g., "it", "that one").\n- If a parameter cannot be extracted, set it to null.\n- Return ONLY valid JSON. No commentary.\n\nReturn JSON in this format:\n{\n    "parameters": {\n        <param_name>: <value or null>\n    },\n    "reasoning": "<brief explanation>"\n}\n',)
